text: Are the Templars the origin of Free Masons? There is is no direct historical connection between the Templars and the Freemasons. These entities are centuries apart and share no common foundationÂ¹âµ. However, there are theories that the Templars infiltrated stone mason guilds after they were suppressed by the Pope and the King of France. These guilds were then refashioned to embrace Templar ideals and rituals, and over time, the masons and Templars became one and the same thingÂ¹. The alleged link between Freemasonry and the Templars has often been used to damage the reputation of masonsâ¶. The Knights Templar, full name The United Religious, Military and Masonic Orders of the Temple and of St John of Jerusalem, Palestine, Rhodes and Malta, is a fraternal order affiliated with Freemasonryâ´. Unlike the initial degrees conferred in a regular Masonic Lodge, which only require a belief in a Supreme Being regardless of religious affiliation, the Knights Templar is one of several additional Masonic Orders in which membership is open only to Freemasons who profess a belief in Christianityâ´. It's important to note that while there are Masonic degrees named after the Knights Templar, not all Knights Templar Orders are Masonicâ¸. The Masonic order of Knights Templar derives its name from the medieval Catholic military order Knights Templar. However, it does not claim any direct lineal descent from the original Templar orderâ´. As Sukkot ends, weâ€™re recommitting to fighting for a world where everyone has a home. We're honoring Mizrahi movement elder Reuven Abergil as he celebrates his 80th birthday for decades of leadership opposing the Israeli governmentâ€™s discrimination against Palestinians and Arab Jews. With his partner Marcelle Edery, Reuven co-founded the Mizrahi Black Panthers and developed close relationships with Palestinians, whom they saw as neighbors and partners. The Panthers understood their oppression as the result of the same Ashkenazi-led Zionist movement that oppressed Palestinians, and they viewed the two liberation struggles as intertwined and interdependent. The same forces that put Arab Jews into negligent and heavily policed transit camps during the 1950s also stole Palestinian land and ethnically cleansed Palestinian communities from their homes. Unlike Ashkenazi Jews who settled in occupied Palestine, Mizrahi and Arab Jews were abandoned in transit camps for years, unable to leave, and subsequently placed in housing they could not own in areas designed to keep them in poverty. Leaders like Reuven Abergil have always resisted Zionist colonization and gentrification, often inspired by or working side by side Palestinian leaders fighting for their right to return to their homes in Palestine. Abergil and the Mizrahi Panthers were the first to meet the Palestinian liberation movement in the 1970â€™s, at a time when it was illegal for Jewish Israelis. Abergil occupied public buildings to demand access to housing. He fought against the dispossession of Palestinians. Well into his 70â€™s, he came to every protest, got arrested, spoke out, encouraged people with his experience. To mark his 80th birthday and his decades of leadership and inspiration, a group of JVP-BIJOCSM members and intergenerational Mizrahi leaders from around the world, are awarding him with The Peopleâ€™s Award. This award is a grassroots, independent initiative to recognize our longtime Mizrahi movement elder. Read more: https://www.estwanathai.com/reuven-award

FOGLIE DI PALMA MILLE IMPIEGHI.
Le foglie di palma non servono solo a riempire le nostre palme, ma sono molto utili anche per andare a comporre la nostra scenografia.
Per esempio per creare il calpestio sotto una palma, per mimare le foglie morte che sono cadute, oppure come elemento di costruzione, io le ho messe sopra al tetto della capanna.
Le foglie di palma sono indispensabili per una scenografia palestine.
Buona sera
-Davide

"Elias Khoury's Gate of the Sun" is considered one of the top 100 Arabic novels in the world. It is a novel that depicts the Palestinian Nakba, portraying the suffering and human tragedy of the Palestinian people. It evokes the Palestinian memory from beneath the rubble of wars, masterfully blending reality and imagination, narrative and incident, ordinary speech and poetic artistic language. The novel revolves around one of the stories of Palestinian infiltrators who attempted to return to Palestine after its occupation in 1948. In the early 1950s, the phenomenon of hidden returnees to their homeland emerged after the initial displacement. However, the tale of the infiltrator and resistance figure Yunis al-Asadi transforms in the novel into a story of love and a symbol of steadfastness, embodying a form of demographic resistance to Zionist existence. "Gate of the Sun" has been translated into several languages.

It's the first time President Biden has used his authority under the REAL ID Act to waive environmental laws, a power established in 2005 previously used by Trump and George W. Bush to build the border wall. In a statement the Center for Biological diversity said, "Every acre of habitat left in the Rio Grande Valley is irreplaceable. We canâ€™t afford to lose more of it to a useless, medieval wall that wonâ€™t do a thing to stop immigration or smuggling. President Bidenâ€™s cynical decision to destroy a wildlife refuge and seal the beautiful Rio Grande behind a grotesque border wall must be stopped.â€

text: ğŸ• Xena: A Survivor's Tale of Resilience Meet Xena, a courageous soul born on May 3, 2022. Her story began with an uncertain start when she and her fellow puppies were left near our shelter. In a twist of fate, July brought a challenge, as she faced a health scare during an operation. Bleeding and in need of care, Xena's strength shone through, and with dedicated foster care, medicine, and nurturing, she triumphed over adversity. With a strong will to live and a spirit that refuses to be held back, Xena is a true survivor. Her resilience speaks volumes about her character, making her an exceptional candidate for a loving home. If you're seeking a companion who embodies strength and determination, consider welcoming Xena into your life. Xena's journey knows no boundaries, and she's open to finding her forever home both locally and abroad. Woodlands International Sales 2023 - record breaking evening! Last night, 25 lots of young horses and embryos were offered at the Woodlands's stables in Koningshooikt, Belgium for the Eleventh Edition of Woodlands International Sales. Auction favorite, 6 year old stallion - Cataki van de Helle, was sold to Czech Republic and became the auction topper at â‚¬400,000. Sambolino H - sold for â‚¬160,000 and Couleur by Belle Fleur NC Z - sold for â‚¬200,000, will be staying in Belgium in the hands of Woodland's loyal belgian costumers. Seven year old stallion, Qornet vd Bisschop found his new home with a new client from Canada. The evening was filled with visitors from around the world, including clients from Ireland, United Kingdom, United States, Palestine, Turkey and Slovakia. We wish all the buyers the best of luck with the horses and hope to see everyone back in 2024! The best is yet to come! #woodlandsinternationalsales #woodlandsreference #woodlands #auction #belgiumhorseauction

Dozens of illegal Jewish settlers, under the protection of Israeli occupation forces, stormed the town of Huwwara last night. A Palestinian youth, who was identified as 19-year-old Labeeb Mohammed Dmaidi, was shot in the heart at the hands of an Israeli settler and was critically injured. Medical sources told WAFA correspondent that Dmaidi was brought to the Rafidia hospital in Nablus in critical condition with a gunshot wound to the heart. Attempts to save Dmaidiâ€™s life failed and he quickly succumbed to his wounds. Moreover, sources at the Palestinian Red Crescent said at least 25 people, including four children, suffocated by tear gas fired by Israeli occupation forces during the settler attack on the town. Dmaidiâ€™s killing brings up the number of Palestinians killed by the Israeli army in less than 24 hours to four. On Thursday morning, Huthayfah Fares, 27, and Abd al-Rahman Atta, 23, were shot dead in the village of Shufa, southeast of Tulkarm. Later in the evening, the Palestinian Ministry of Health confirmed that a young Palestinian man was shot dead by Israeli occupation forces. A week in review at Gift of the Givers: ğŸ‡¿ğŸ‡¦: Gift of the Givers is actively assisting the Western Cape flood victims. ğŸ‡²ğŸ‡¼: Gift of the Givers is providing safe drinking water to rural communities in Malawi by drilling nine boreholes in Chikwawa District. These villages were chosen with the Department of Water's help, focusing on farming communities lacking access to clean water. Many residents currently rely on rivers and shallow wells, which are unsafe due to animal contamination. ğŸ‡µğŸ‡¸: Gift of the Givers partnered with a private company in India for slaughtering, packing, and freezing Qurbani meat. It was subsequently shipped to Palestine and distributed to needy families, offering them much-needed protein-rich food, renewed strength, and hope. #Syria: Gift of the Givers distributed thousands of school bags filled with essential supplies to disadvantaged students in Northern Syria as part of our Education Support Programme. These school bags, containing pens, notebooks, and crucial supplies, enable children to pursue their education despite the disruptions caused by war and displacement. For these students, these basic learning tools make a significant impact. ğŸ‡¾ğŸ‡ª: In war-torn Yemen, Gift of the Givers dedicated team is tirelessly distributing emergency food parcels to displaced families in camps. With over 16 million people at risk of food insecurity this year, our consistent food distributions are a lifeline for vulnerable families facing the threat of starvation. ğŸ‡¿ğŸ‡¼: Gift of the Givers team swiftly addressed Hopley's urgent clean water needs during the dry summer months. This area grapples with a chronic water shortage due to reliance on shallow wells, limited boreholes, and the use of unsafe water from the Mukuvisi River, worsened by high population density, which strains the existing boreholes ğŸ‡¸ğŸ‡´: Gift of the Givers distributed food parcels in Kismayo, Jubbaland State, providing essential items like rice, canned fish, baked beans, cooking oil, and porridge to vulnerable families in urgent need. This initiative aimed to address their immediate nutritional needs and offer support during challenging times. text: IJV is proud to be co-sponsoring screenings of the film Israelism! Focusing on the stories of two young Americans raised to defend Israel at all costs, Israelism traces their awakening to Israel's dehumanization of Palestinians and the ongoing violence of the occupation. The film asks how and why Israel became the cornerstone of American Judaism, what the consequences have been, and what will happen as divisions continue to grow. Watch Israelism virtually, hosted by Voices from the Holy Land, and join us for an IJV co-sponsored online Q&A discussion on October 15 at 3pm ET. Hamas guidelines for Palestinian use and manipulation of social media According to their guidelines: â€œAnyone killed or martyred is to be called a civilian from Gaza or Palestine, before we talk about his status in jihad or his military rank. Donâ€™t forget to always add â€˜innocent civilianâ€™ or â€˜innocent citizenâ€™ in your description of those killed in Israeli attacks on Gaza.â€ The guidelines urge : â€œAvoid publishing pictures of rockets fired into Israel from city centers. This [would] provide a pretext for attacking residential areas in the Gaza Strip. Do not publish or share photos or video clips showing rocket launching sites or the movement of resistance [forces] in Gaza.â€ Hamas also prepared a series of suggestions specifically for Palestinian activists who speak to Westerners via social media. The ministry emphasizes that conversations with them should be conducted differently from conversations with other Arabs. It stated: "When speaking to the West, you must use political, rational, and persuasive discourse, and avoid emotional discourse aimed at begging for sympathy. There are elements with a conscience in the world; you must maintain contact with them and activate them for the benefit of Palestine. Their role is to shame the occupation and expose its violations. "Avoid entering into a political argument with a Westerner aimed at convincing him that the Holocaust is a lie and deceit; instead, equate it with Israel's crimes against Palestinian civilians. "The narrative of life vs. the narrative of blood: [When speaking] to an Arab friend, start with the number of martyrs. [But when speaking] to a Western friend, start with the number of wounded and dead. Be sure to humanize the Palestinian suffering. Try to paint a picture of the suffering of the civilians in Gaza and the West Bank during the occupation's operations and its bombings of cities and villages. "Do not publish photos of military commanders. Do not mention their names in public, and do not praise their achievements in conversations with foreign friends!" Be cynical about what you read. Be cynical about what you believe.

Teague Marching Invitational set for Saturday The third annual Teague Marching Invitational will be held this Saturday, Oct. 7, at Lion Stadium. Prelims performances start at 9 a.m. and will conclude at 4:30 p.m. The Top 10 bands will advance to the finals. Finals will take place at 6:30 p.m. and conclude at 9:45 p.m. The Teague High School Band will perform at 5:45 p.m. that afternoon. Teagueâ€™s 2023 UIL marching show is entitled "Heist" and features music from Beethoven, Billie Eilish and Coolio. The music was written by Luke McMillan and show design was coordinated by Clayton Harris. There are 27 high school bands ranging from Class 2A-4A at the marching contest. The bands competing are Academy, Buffalo, Bullard, Cayuga, Centerville, Corrigan-Camden, Cross Roads, Eustace, Frankston, Giddings, Hillsboro, Kemp, Kerens, La Vega, Lorena, Mineola, Mount Enterprise, Navasota, Palestine, Palmer, Rogers, Rosebud-Lott, Shepherd, Valley Mills, Westwood, Whitney, & Wortham. The Sound of Navarro will be our College Exhibition Band. Cory Hiles is in his fourth year as the Director of Bands at Teague ISD. He also served as an assistant band director for two years earlier in his career. According to Hiles, this is the most bands ever to attend the Teague Marching Invitational; doubling last year's numbers. â€œAs always, I am very excited about hosting this contest. I always look forward to this time every year hosting this contest because I love marching band season. Most people dread organizing something like this because there is a lot of work that myself, staff, boosters, parents, and my high school band students put into this. But, I find it as a â€˜good stressâ€™ to have, especially when I get to watch other bands perform. It's about giving back and doing a service to band programs like these that want to get better prepared for their best UIL Region/UIL Area performance,â€ Hiles said. â€œWe have nothing really to gain from this, except give other directors and their respective band programs an opportunity to shine on a big stage and feel confident in their preparation for the UIL competitive marching season. But, it also puts our great community and our school district on the map when it comes to hosting a big event such as this. It definitely wouldn't be possible with the support of our Teague ISD administration, faculty & staff, Teague Athletics, and our Teague Band Boosters and parents and students & for that I truly am grateful.â€ Admission to the contest for all spectators is $3. Educators, first responders, and military personnel can get in for free upon badge or credentials. Senior citizens (65 or older) and children under the age of 3 are admitted for free as well.

Until May 2023, around 200 people lived in Ein Samiya. It was a Palestinian community based on sheep farming. They could no longer bear the violence and terror of the settlers and were forced to leave their lands a few months ago. This community consists mostly of refugees who were forcibly displaced from the Negev/ Al-Naqab in 1948. They were continuously displaced ever since until they finally found their place in Ein Samiya, east of Ramallah and near the village of Taybeh. The settlements of Rimonim and Kochav HaShahar in the area continually expanded, establishing "outposts" and "shepherd farms" around Ein Samiya with the clear aim of displacing Palestinians. The community endured years of daily abuse by the settlers, who restricted their access to water, grazed their sheep on their land and inside their homes, threatened them with weapons to hinder grazing, and instilled fear in their families. The Israeli army, which ostensibly should protect the population in the occupied territory allowed and sometimes even assisted in this abuse through frequent arrests, property confiscation, and other means. In May of this year, the community, which had endured systematic abuse for years, fled out of fear and due to the impossibility of sustaining themselves or grazing their sheep. As they left Ein Samiya, settlers continued their campaign of terror, preventing the community's return. Most of Ein Samiya's residents relocated near Qufar Ma'alec in Area B, wedged between a massive quarry and a garbage incineration site. The environment is toxic, living conditions are unbearable, and they were forced to sell most of their livestock. Some members of the community dispersed to other areas in Jericho and Taybeh. This marks yet another tragic chapter in the decades-long saga of continuous occupation, Zionist expansion, and the expulsion of Palestinians. "Shepherd farms" in the West Bank are illegal outposts, often established on "state lands" or even private Palestinian lands. Despite the pastoral image the term evokes, these farms are a means of colonial dispossession, upholding Jewish supremacy in the West Bank. The strategy is simple: a few people occupy vast amounts of land. In 2021, the director of the settlers' organization, Amanah, openly admitted this, stating, "A single shepherd farm preserves thousands of dunams of land." Israeli governments have consistently supported and enabled this expansionist practice, further perpetuating the issue. Under the current settler government, overt support for outposts has increased, with many being officially recognized this year. This has led to a surge in settler violence, as they feel they have unlimited government backing. These actions mirror past expansion of Jewish settlements prior to the 1948 war and are part of a broader process of ethnic cleansing. Colonial organizations like KKL-JNF are also involved in these efforts. https://www.haaretz.co.il/news/politics/2023-09-22/ty-article-magazine/.premium/0000018a-b310-d13d-a98f-fbb560860000 What can I do? This link will take you to the book, "Absolute Solitude: Selected Poems," by Dulce MarÃ­a Loynaz. https://amzn.to/46vR23h:=:https://www.amazon.com/dp/0914671227/ref=tsm_1_fb_lk Dulce MarÃ­a Loynaz MuÃ±oz (Havana, Cuba; 10 December 1902 â€“ 27 April 1997) was a Cuban poet, and is considered one of the principal figures of Cuban literature. She was awarded the Miguel de Cervantes Prize in 1992. She earned her Doctorate in Civil Law at University of Havana in 1927. Early life Dulce MarÃ­a Loynaz was the daughter of the famous General Enrique Loynaz del Castillo, a hero of the Cuban Liberation Army and author of the lyrics of the march theme, "El Himno Invasor", and sister of poet Enrique Loynaz MuÃ±oz. Dulce MarÃ­a was born in Havana, Cuba on December 10, 1902, to a family of great sensibility towards artistic and cultural manifestations and deep patriotic feelings. Homeschooled as a child, Loynaz grew up in a familiar environment highly propitious for poetry. Although Loynaz had a sheltered childhood, her early adulthood was much more adventurous, including experiences available at that time only to wealthy young women, even outside of Cuba. She published a number of poems in her teens and twenties. Education She completed the Doctorate of Civil Law at the University of Havana in 1927, but rarely practiced law, and stopped practicing altogether in 1961 out of dislike. She was able to travel widely. In addition, her talents and her family's social position brought her into personal contact with some of the major Spanish-language authors of the century, including Spanish author Federico GarcÃ­a Lorca, Chilean poet Gabriela Mistral who won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1945, Cuban author Alejo Carpentier, and the Spanish writer Juan RamÃ³n JimÃ©nez who won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1956. Publications and Poetry Loynaz published her first poems in "La NaciÃ³n" in 1920. She traveled extensively including to Turkey, Syria, Libya, Palestine, and Egypt. Loynaz also visited Mexico in 1937 and various countries in South America from 1946 to 1947, and the Canary Islands in 1947 and 1951 where she as declared adoptive daughter. Loynaz began writing "Jardin" in 1928 and completed the novel in 1935, shortly after Cuban women obtained the right to vote. During these early decades of the twentieth century, a time of great feminist activity, a dynamic and effective women's movement flourished in Cuba, and women's rights became part of the Cuban political consciousness. The feminist attitude Loynaz displays in "Jardin" is tied strongly to the image of the city. The novel begins and ends with the heroine looking out from the garden toward a city that resembles Havana. In 1950, she published weekly chronicles at different publications (truncated)

text: I took part in an interesting conference of The Israeli Committee Against House Demolitions (ICAHD). Here you can watch my and other presentations. I begin in minute 51:30: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kcz5XN-RQ4U Here it is as a written text: The Zionist left destroyed Palestine; The right will burry the Zionist enterprise? The Zionist movement was colonial and European from its inception. It succeeded managed to join the British, who sought to control the country, and turned the zionists into their settler arm. Settler colonialism in Palestine was implemented through the division of labor: the British were the colonial empire, and the Zionists were the settlers who put the plan into action. Since the 1920s, the Zionists "redeemed the land," meaning they bought land parcels exclusively for Jews and "conquered" them, which meant Jewish settled on these lands. This involved the displacement of Palestinian Arabs from these lands, who lived legally on them many years, even though they werenâ€™t their owners. Most of the "pioneers" settlers in labor groups and kibbutzim in the 1920s and 1930s were leftists, including Hashomer Hatzair and others. The leadership of the Jewish community prior to the state (HaYishuv in Hebrew) was Ashkenazi secular and anti-religious, with elements of anti-Semitism (which also manifested itself in nowadays). The Zionist movement had no interest in the culture and history of the country and certainly not in its Palestinian inhabitants. The land was the place to conquer in order establish the Jewish national home. Hatred of Arabs, Orientalism, continued after the establishment of the state and towards Arab Jews too, with the concept of the melting pot whose goal was to civilize Arab Jews, that is, to turn them into Europeans and to eliminate their Arabness. Until 1948, the future of Palestine was uncertain, but with the UN Partition Resolution its fate was doomed. The Palestinians could not accept a plan that took away half of their land. Arab countries, Jewish communists and ultra-religious Jews opposed it, but the plan was accepted by the United Nations. From there, the land deteriorated into severe violence between Zionists and Palestinians. The power balance favored the Zionists, and also because Palestinians perceived the whole region as their home, they were expelled and lost their homes. The Zionists destroyed Palestine and took control of 78% of the land. This was all done under the leadership of the Zionist left. Despite the expulsion of 750,000 Palestinians, who were the majority of the land's inhabitants, and the establishment of a Jewish state, the Zionists in the Declaration of Independence promised peace with their Arab neighbors and safeguarding the rights of all inhabitants. These words were empty from the moment they were written, but they were good enough for the international community to support the new Jewish state. This support was partly motivated by anti-Semitic sentiments - a preference for Jews being away from Europe - and feelings of guilt over the Holocaust. As long as the left led the country and continued to promote the false narrative of seeking peace, the world supported Israel. Even during the Suez Crisis and the occupation of Sinai in 1956, Britain and France supported Israel. In 1967, Israel completed the occupation of Palestine, and immediately afterward, despite hesitations and debates, whether honest or not regarding withdrawal, established settlements in the West Bank. Again, it was the Labor Party that led the way. Still, as long as Israel conveyed that it desired peace within the framework of two states, the world accepted it. In 1977, a political turn-over occurred, and the right-wing came to power. Under Begin's leadership, the only significant Israeli de-colonial move took place: withdrawal of the Sinai Peninsula in exchange for peace with Egypt. Since the completion of the occupation in 1967 the settler movement Gush Emunim, led by rabbi Zvi Yehuda Kook, saw in the expansion to new territories as messianic sings and pushed to establish settlement in The West Bank and later in Gaza Strip. While the political left used the religious component as a mobilizing one, and thatâ€™s why the Uganda option was changed by "Eretz Israel", the hard core settling movement took it as their core project and got the support of Labor government to establish settlements. The governments of the right, and especially the current government, is pushing Israel towards a direction it has not attempted before. This direction was well articulated in the "Submission Plan" written by Bezalel Smotrich a few years ago. According to that plan, Israel would hack the hopes of the Palestinians for an independent state and take full control of the West Bank. It suggests that Palestinians should be encouraged to emigrate voluntarily from the "Land of Israel," with Israel providing generous economic support and vocational training for those who choose to leave. (truncated)

Occupied Palestinian Town of Huwwara Under Attack Again â€“ Developing Storyâ€¼ï¸Last February, hundreds of Israeli settlers stormed the town of Huwwara, killing one Palestinian and wounding many othersâ€¼ï¸Today, October 5, dozens of settlers, under the protection of the Israeli military, are back in Huwwaraâ€¼ï¸ Dozens of Israeli Jewish settlers, along with a large number of Israeli soldiers, stormed on Thursday night the town of Huwwara, located near to the occupied West Bank city of Nablus. Thursday night, Israeli occupation forces stormed Huwwara, killing a young Palestinian man, the official Palestinian news agency WAFA reported. Israeli occupation forces reportedly imposed an extensive lockdown on Palestinian businesses in Huwwara and tightened their restrictions at military checkpoints around the city of Nablus. Later in the evening, the Palestinian Ministry of Health confirmed that a young Palestinian man was shot dead by Israeli occupation forces. His identity is yet to be confirmed. WAFA correspondent said that Israeli occupation forces opened fire at a young man after surrounding him in a building near the Zaytouna Roundabout in the town of Huwwara. The soldiers reportedly blocked access to ambulance crews, leaving the wounded young man bleeding to death, according to eyewitnesses, cited by WAFA. This is the third Palestinian killed in 24 hours by Israeli occupation forcesâ€™ gunfire. On Thursday morning, Huthayfah Fares, 27, and Abd al-Rahman Atta, 23, were shot dead in the village of Shufa, southeast of Tulkarm. The Israeli military raid on Huwwara was followed by the storming of the town by dozens of illegal Jewish settlers. According to Aljazeera Arabic, the ongoing assault on Palestinian homes and other properties by the settlers is happening under the protection of the Israeli military. This is a developing story and the Palestine Chronicle will keep its readers updated. https://www.palestinechronicle.com/palestinian-town-of-huwwara-under-attack-again-developing-story/

â In Sept 2012, on the 30th anniversary of the massacre at Sabra and Shatila refugee camps in Beirut, I wrote a letter to the Israeli soldiers who were on duty there. This September 2023, on the 41st anniversary of that massacre, we mark another atrocity in a Palestinian refugee camp, this one in Jenin, in the Occupied Territories. I am again writing a letter but this time to those Israeli soldiers on active duty who were in Jenin. Fifty years ago today, a war erupted in the Middle East that changed not just the region, but the world. Itâ€™s a war of many names, depending on who you ask: the October War, the Yom Kippur War, the Ramadan War, or the 1973 Arab-Israeli War.â 
.â 
The warâ€™s victor is just as disputed. It began with a two-pronged attack against Israel by Egypt and Syria.â 
Egypt attacked from the south, to take back the Sinai Peninsula, and Syria from the north, to take back the Golan Heights.â 
.â 
Israel had captured both six years prior in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, alongside occupying what remained of historic Palestine.â 
.â 
The recently formed state was riding high on that victory: it never anticipated an attack like this, especially not during Yom Kippur, an auspicious day for Jews. Meanwhile, the politics of the Cold War played in the background.â 
.â 
The Soviets supplied the Arab countries with weapons and the United States backed Israel. The two sides were on the brink of military conflict for the first time since the so-called Cuban Missile Crisis in 1962.â

South Africans of faith must acknowledge that Israeli policies towards Palestinians are a carbon copy of the apartheid-era policies in South Africa or risk becoming complicit in the subjugation of Palestinians, the leader of the Anglican Church of Southern Africa (ACSA) has said.

In a statement released on 29 September, Thabo Makgoba, the Anglican Archbishop of Cape Town, said that the Church had recognised Israel as an apartheid state.

â€œAs people of faith who are distressed by the pain of the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza - and who long for security and a just peace for both Palestine and Israel - we can no longer ignore the realities on the ground,â€ Makgoba said.

â€œOur hearts ache for our Christian brothers and sisters in Palestine, whose numbers include Anglicans but are rapidly declining. People of all faiths in South Africa have both a deep understanding of what it is to live under oppression,â€ he continued, before comparing Israel to South Africa under apartheid rule.

â€œWhen black South Africans who have lived under apartheid visit Israel, the parallels to apartheid are impossible to ignore. If we stand by and keep quiet, we will be complicit in the continuing oppression of the Palestinians,â€ Makgoba added.

While the South African Zionist Organisation lashed out at the resolution, with its chairperson calling the resolution "appalling" and "antisemitic" - other civil society groups like the Palestine Solidarity Committee and South African BDS Coalition, warmly welcomed the decision.

The Anglican Church said its stance was not an attack on Jewish people, "but to the policies of Israelis' governments, which are becoming ever more extreme".

"We salute the Anglican Church for not only calling out Israeli apartheid but also taking action,â€ South Africa's BDS Coalition said.

"The Anglican Church of Southern Africa is standing on the right side of history, fully supporting the Palestinian struggle for equality, human rights and justice," the coalition added.

The UN's special rapporteurs and several human rights organisations, such as Amnesty International, have concluded that Israel practises apartheid

Herodium is a palace-fortress and town located in Palestine, built by Herod the Great between 23-15 BC. It consists of the upper palace-fortress situated on the hill, overlooking a large pool complex in the lower Herodium, a lower palace, residential buildings, a theatre, and a synagogue

As only one of two Levantine states flanking the Mediterranean Sea, Lebanon's geographic location is of great interest to the various road, rail, and waterway connectivity projects emerging in West Asia - not only in connecting the region, but as a bridge between Asia and Europe.

A second look, however, reveals a massive land access problem for Lebanon, which can only be reached via the territories of Syria and Occupied Palestine. Clearly then, for Lebanon to actively participate in West Asian connectivity initiatives, it must establish robust links with either of these two countries.

While Palestine is not a practical or feasible option for the time being, Syria remains Lebanon's only territorial means for the import and export of goods. However, more than a decade of conflict in Syria, persisting foreign occupation of its territories, and US-imposed Caesar Act sanctions have posed immense challenges to historic Lebanese-Syrian political and economic relations.

#onthisdayinhistory The Yom Kippur War began with an Egyptian and Syrian attack on land held by Israel from the Six Day War on October 6, 1973. In 1967, Israel launched a preemptive strike against Egypt in the Six Day War and subsequently occupied the Sinai Peninsula, the entirety of Palestine, and the Golan Heights. The capture of the Sinai Peninsula was a massive blunder for Egypt as they had to shut down the Suez Canal in its entirety. The war ended with both sides agreeing to a ceasefire. 

Both Egyptian and Syrian military planners saw a window of opportunity to attack Israel due to the ongoing Jewish holiday of Yom Kippur. Egypt in particular hoped to capture the eastern bank of the Suez Canal in order to leverage Israel into giving back the occupied Sinai Peninsula. As Egyptian forces advanced into the Sinai Peninsula, Syrian forces attacked the Israeli-occupied Golan Heights. After three days of heavy fighting, Israel halted the Egyptian advance and pushed Syria back to the pre-war ceasefire line. Israel then launched a four-day counteroffensive into Syria and managed to start shelling the Syrian capital of Damascus. Egyptian forces attempted a breakout, but failed and Israeli forces then pushed into Egypt. An October 22 United Nations brokered ceasefire fell apart, with each side blaming the other. As the Israelis pushed more and more towards the Egyptian capital of Cairo, tensions between the US (who supported Israel) and the Soviet Union (who supported Egypt) rose as well. A second ceasefire was imposed on October 25, which was far more successful and ended the war. 

The Yom Kippur War had some long-reaching impacts. Despite facing yet another humiliating defeat from Israel, the Arab powers did feel some sense of vindication with their early successes. Israel also accepted the fact that there may come a time when their military is not as dominant as previously believed. Both of these changes led to the beginning of an Israeli-Palestinian peace process and the 1978 Camp David Accords, where Israel agreed to give the Sinai Peninsula back to Egypt in exchange for Egypt recognizing Israel as a legitimate state. #yomkippurwar #israel #egypt #syria

At least 80 people were killed in a drone attack on the Military Academy in Homs on Thursday, during a cadet graduation ceremony, according to official Syrian media. The Syrian Ministry of Health announced that the death toll had risen to 89, with 277 injured.

The attack occurred at the end of the ceremony, according to the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (SOHR), which estimated that 123 were killed, including 54 civilians, and 150 wounded.

The Syrian government declared three days of national mourning. Foreign Minister Faisal Mekdad spoke with Iranian Foreign Minister Hossein Amir-Abdollahian, who condemned the attack, according to SANA. Condemnations were also issued by the Sultanate of Oman, the United Arab Emirates, the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, the Islamic Jihad Movement in Palestine, and the General Conference of Arab Parties.

While no party has claimed responsibility, the Syrian Ministry of Foreign Affairs accused â€œterrorist organizations supported by the American occupation and other international parties, united in shedding Syrian blood.â€ Media outlets close to the Syrian regime indirectly accused the â€œTurkistan Islamic Partyâ€, and the regimeâ€™s army announced the bombing of the partyâ€™s headquarters in Idlib and the Aleppo countryside, as well as those of the Muhajireen Battalion. These are the two factions possessing drone technology, according to sources who spoke to the Al-Alam News Network.

In response, Syrian forces targeted towns in Idlib Governorate and the western countryside of Aleppo, killing eight, according to SOHR. The White Helmets said on their Facebook pages that a bombing on the town of Kafr Nouran killed five civilians, wounding others. The bombing of Darat Izza killed three civilians and wounded more than ten, while a bombing on Sarmin led to one death and wounded others.

The northwestern fronts have seen an escalation recently, due to attempts by regime and opposition forces to advance on contact lines in the countryside of Latakia and Idlib. Regime forcesâ€™ attacks on the region in recent weeks have killed 63 civilians, including 11 children, and injured more than 280 others.

RAMALLAH, Palestine (AFP) - A Palestinian was martyred early Friday during clashes with Israeli soldiers and settlers in a town that has been the scene of frequent violence in the occupied West Bank, multiple sources said.

"Labib Mohammad Labib Dmidi, 19, was shot in the heart by settlers in the town of Huwara," the Palestinian health ministry said in a brief statement.

The Israeli army said in a statement that a suspect had been shot by soldiers, and a military spokesman said later he was unable to confirm whether the Palestinian had been killed or wounded.

1st Reading: Baruch 1:15-22

The book of Baruch is attributed to Baruch, son of Neriah, the scribe who served Jeremiah the Prophet (Jer 32:12) and who wrote down his words (Jer 36:4).Â  Most scholars date it to the late second to mid-first century BC. 

According to its introduction (see 1:1-14), it was written in Babylon by Baruch after the deportation and sent to Jerusalem to be read at liturgical gatherings. The opening verses of this book ascribe it, or at least its first part, to Baruch, well-known as the secretary of the prophet Jeremiah. It contains five very different compositions, the first and the last in prose, the others in poetic form. The prose sections were certainly composed in Hebrew, though the earliest known form of the book is in Greek. 

Today, we have the first of two readings from the book. It is the beginning of what is called The Prayer of the Exiles, the exiles being those Jews who were deported to Babylon from Judah and Jerusalem by King Nebuchadnezzar in the 6th century BC. As the passage seems to belong to a much later date, it may rather reflect the feelings of a later community who saw in their own situation a similarity with those exiles. 

The details he gives indicate the year 582 BC, probably in the fifth month, the anniversary of the fall of Jerusalem, which was doubtless commemorated among the exiles as it was in Palestine The passage is a general lament for the situation of the Israelites now living in exile, far from their homeland and from Jerusalem and its Temple, the home of Yahweh. But there is no complaint against Yahweh for their condition. Their sufferings are due to one reason and one reason only â€“ the peopleâ€™s long history of not obeying the Lord and going their own way. This began from the days the Lord brought them out of Egypt right up to the present time. 

The writer compares the goodness and the integrity of God with that of his people. If they have suffered by being sent into exile, it is the result of their own sins and not the doing of the good God. In our response to this reading, we might reflect on how much of our own pain and misfortunes can be traced to our own behavior, individually or corporately.

@radioalhara Ø±Ø§Ø¯ÙŠÙˆ Ø§Ù„Ø­Ø§Ø±Ø© - Interview with artist Helena Martin Franco

https://soundcloud.com/freecityradio/radio-alhara-interview-with-artist-helena-martin-franco

Broadcast today, Oct. 6th at 3pm in Bethlehem, Palestine and 8am eastern time. Also aired in the past month on both @ckutmtl 90.3 FM and @cjlo1690am, broadcast times on write up at bottom.

An interview with artist and activist Helena Martin Franco @frittacaro. In this exchange Helena speaks about the process and the ideas behind the show Freehand Absence/Ausencia a mano alzada that showed in summer 2023 at the PHI Foundation for Contemporary Art. This show explores the silences in Helena's family past but also the ways that silences surrounding injustices, particularly relating to gender based violence, are embodied and carried across generations. Information on the show and Helena's work here: helenamartinfranco.com

The accompanying image is a section of a photograph taken by Richard-Max Tremblay of the exhibition by Helena in question.

Music on this edition is Passage by Anarchist Mountains.

Stefan contributes artist interviews to @radioalhara in Palestine that broadcast on the first Friday of each month at 10:30am eastern time, 5:30pm in Palestine (www.radioalhara.net). Also these interviews air on the third Friday of each month at 11am on @ckutmtl 90.3FM in Montreal (ckut.ca) and on the second Tuesday of each month on @cjlo1690am at 1:30pm also in Montreal.

O LITTLE TOWN OF BETHLEHEM
16x20" oil on canvas. 
Featured in our October 21st group show 
MAKEâ¤ï¸NOT WAR 
Inquiries welcome. 

Listening to Christmas carols, watching footage of missile strikes in Bethlehem, and Ukraine, and imagining a new born baby, in a shed, and a newly delivered mother cradling her child against the bullets and shrapnel.
Their only protection is a blessing. 
Taking influence from Raphael and Da Vinci, a chubby cherub protects them from the silent stars.

Nebuchadnezzar II (r. 605-562 BC); known as the greatest king of the Chaldean Dynasty (626-539 BC) of Babylonia. He conquered Syria and Palestine and made Babylon a splendid city.

In 587 BC, Nebuchadnezzar destroyed the Kingdom of Judah, and its capital, Jerusalem. The destruction of Jerusalem led to the Babylonian captivity as the city's population, and people from the surrounding lands, were deported to Babylonia.

Because Babylon, well within his own territory, had been the target of most of his military campaigns and had caused the death of his son, Sennacherib destroyed the city in 689 BC.

In Mythology :

Nebuchadnezzar II was noted for conquering one of greatest djinn of the ancient world,Â King Solomon. However he was unpopular because after he did so, Nebuchadnezzar destroyed Jeruselam and stole theÂ Solomon's Grimoire. King Nebuchadnezzar built the Ishtar Gate in Babylon in the honor of the firstÂ Blue Djinn, but in his self-pride he also built himself a magnificant palace. This angered the Blue Djinn because he built himself a greater palace than her own.

As a punishment, he is forced to stay in theÂ IravotumÂ and has been there for millennia. He only survives because he, literally, has nothing to be desired. In John's travels in the Iravotum to rescue his sister, he meets him. he also thinks grass is regular food.

(The Children of the Lamp)

.â 
The warâ€™s victor is just as disputed. It began with a two-pronged attack against Israel by Egypt and Syria.â 
Egypt attacked from the south, to take back the Sinai Peninsula, and Syria from the north, to take back the Golan Heights.â 
.â

.â

Posted @withregram â€¢ @middleeasteye South Africans of faith must acknowledge that Israeli policies towards Palestinians are a carbon copy of the apartheid-era policies in South Africa or risk becoming complicit in the subjugation of Palestinians, the leader of the Anglican Church of Southern Africa (ACSA) has said.

In a statement released on 29 September, Thabo Makgoba, the Anglican Archbishop of Cape Town, said that the Church had recognised Israel as an apartheid state.

â€œAs people of faith who are distressed by the pain of the occupation of the West Bank and Gaza - and who long for security and a just peace for both Palestine and Israel - we can no longer ignore the realities on the ground,â€ Makgoba said.

â€œOur hearts ache for our Christian brothers and sisters in Palestine, whose numbers include Anglicans but are rapidly declining. People of all faiths in South Africa have both a deep understanding of what it is to live under oppression,â€ he continued, before comparing Israel to South Africa under apartheid rule.

â€œWhen black South Africans who have lived under apartheid visit Israel, the parallels to apartheid are impossible to ignore. If we stand by and keep quiet, we will be complicit in the continuing oppression of the Palestinians,â€ Makgoba added.

While the South African Zionist Organisation lashed out at the resolution, with its chairperson calling the resolution "appalling" and "antisemitic" - other civil society groups like the Palestine Solidarity Committee and South African BDS Coalition, warmly welcomed the decision.

The Anglican Church said its stance was not an attack on Jewish people, "but to the policies of Israelis' governments, which are becoming ever more extreme".

"We salute the Anglican Church for not only calling out Israeli apartheid but also taking action,â€ South Africa's BDS Coalition said.

"The Anglican Church of Southern Africa is standing on the right side of history, fully supporting the Palestinian struggle for equality, human rights and justice," the coalition added.

The UN's special rapporteurs and several human rights organisations, such as Amnesty International, have concluded that Israel practises apartheid

Third longest-serving Palestinian prisoner in Israel begins 39th year behind bars

Wafa
October 6, 2023

RAMALLAH, Friday, October 6, 2023 (WAFA) - Sixty-six-year-old Muhammad Altus, the third longest-serving Palestinian prisoner in Israel, began today his 39th year behind bars, according to the Palestinian Prisoner Society (PPS).

Altus, from Jabaa village in the south of the West Bank, was arrested on October 6, 1985 for resisting the Israeli occupation as part of Fatah fighters. He was shot and severely injured when he was arrested and then sentenced to life in prison.

His wife died in 2015 after being in a coma for one year and he has three children who were small when he was arrested but today are married and have brought him nine grandchildren, but they cannot visit him in prison because they are second-degree relatives.

According to the PPS, Altus is one of 26 Palestinians who have been in prison since before the signing of the Oslo peace accords in 1993 between the Palestine Liberation Organization and Israel and whom Israel has refused to set free in any prisonersâ€™ release or exchange deal.

During his long years of detention, Altus was subjected to all forms of torture and acts of vengeance; aside from the serious injury he sustained during his arrest in 1985, he was subjected to harsh and long interrogations, his family home was demolished three times, and he was denied release in any prisoners' swap deal that were made during his incarceration, the latest of which was the prisoners swap of 2014, when Israel reneged on the release of the fourth batch of prisoners, which included Altus.

The first two longest-serving Palestinian resistance prisoners in Israel are Karim Younis, who has been behind bars for 38 years, and his cousin, Maher Younis, also 38 years behind bars, from the Palestinian town of Ara inside Israel.
